         <abstract>
            <p>The 3x + 1 function T(x) takes the values (3x + 1)/2 if x is odd and x/2 if x is even. Let a be any integer with &lt;tex-math&gt;$a \not\equiv 0 (\operatorname{mod} 3)$&lt;/tex-math&gt;. If n&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;(a) counts the number of n with T&lt;sup&gt;(k)&lt;/sup&gt;(n) = a, then for all sufficiently large k, (1.302)&lt;sup&gt;k&lt;/sup&gt; ≤ n&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt; (a) ≤ (1.359)&lt;sup&gt;k&lt;/sup&gt;. If π&lt;sub&gt;a&lt;/sub&gt;(x) counts the number of n with |n| ≤ x which eventually reach a under iteration by T, then for sufficiently large x, π&lt;sub&gt;a&lt;/sub&gt;(x) ≥ x&lt;sup&gt;.65&lt;/sup&gt;). The proofs are computer-intensive.</p>
          </abstract>
